Subject Content
3.1 Physical Chemistry
3.1.1 Atomic Structure
3.1.1.1 Fundamental Particles
Protons, neutrons and electrons: relative charge and relative mass
An atom consists of a nucleus containing protons and neutrons surrounded by electrons
3.1.1.2 Mass Number and Isotopes
Mass number (A) and atomic (proton) number (Z)
Determine number of fundamental particles in atoms and ions using A, Z and charge
Explain the existence of isotopes
Principles of a simple time of flight (TOF) mass spectrometer: ionisation → acceleration (constant KE) → ion drift → ion detection → data analysis
Mass spectrometry gives accurate information about relative isotopic mass and relative abundance of isotopes
Used to identify elements and determine relative molecular mass
Interpret simple mass spectra of elements
Calculate relative atomic mass from isotopic abundance (limited to mononuclear ions)
3.1.1.3 Electron Configuration
Electron configurations of atoms and ions up to Z = 36 in terms of shells and sub-shells (s, p, d orbitals)
Ionisation energies:
Define first ionisation energy
Write equations for first and successive ionisation energies
Explain how first and successive ionisation energies in Period 3 (Na–Ar) and Group 2 (Be–Ba) give evidence for electron configuration in sub-shells and shells
3.1.2 Amount of Substance
3.1.2.1 Relative Atomic Mass and Relative Molecular Mass
Relative atomic mass and relative molecular mass in terms of ¹²C
Relative formula mass used for ionic compounds
Define Ar and Mr
3.1.2.2 The Mole and the Avogadro Constant
Avogadro constant = number of particles in a mole
The mole applied to electrons, atoms, molecules, ions, formulas and equations
Concentration measured in mol dm⁻³
Calculations using: Avogadro constant; mass, Mr and moles; concentration, volume and moles
3.1.2.3 The Ideal Gas Equation
pV = nRT (variables in SI units)
Use the equation in calculations
3.1.2.4 Empirical and Molecular Formula
Empirical formula: simplest whole number ratio of atoms of each element
Molecular formula: actual number of atoms of each element
Calculate empirical formula from composition by mass or percentage by mass
Calculate molecular formula from empirical formula and Mr
3.1.2.5 Balanced Equations and Associated Calculations
Full and ionic equations
Percentage atom economy = (molecular mass of desired product ÷ sum of molecular masses of all reactants) × 100
Economic, ethical and environmental advantages of high atom economy
Balance equations for studied and unfamiliar reactions
Calculations: masses, volumes of gases, percentage yields, percentage atom economies, concentrations and volumes for reactions in solutions
Required Practical 1: Make up a volumetric solution and carry out a simple acid–base titration.

3.1.3 Bonding
3.1.3.1 Ionic Bonding
Electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions in a lattice
Formulas of compound ions: sulfate, hydroxide, nitrate, carbonate, ammonium
Predict charge on simple ions from Periodic Table position
Construct formulas for ionic compounds
3.1.3.2 Nature of Covalent and Dative Covalent Bonds
Single covalent bond = shared pair of electrons
Multiple bonds = multiple pairs of electrons
Co-ordinate (dative covalent) bond = shared pair with both electrons from one atom
Represent covalent bond with a line; co-ordinate bond with an arrow
3.1.3.3 Metallic Bonding
Attraction between delocalised electrons and positive ions arranged in a lattice
3.1.3.4 Bonding and Physical Properties
Four types of crystal structure:

Ionic (e.g. sodium chloride)
Metallic (e.g. magnesium)
Macromolecular / giant covalent (e.g. diamond, graphite)
Molecular (e.g. ice, iodine)
Students should:

Relate melting point and conductivity to structure type and bonding
Explain energy changes associated with changes of state
Draw diagrams to represent these structures
3.1.3.5 Shapes of Simple Molecules and Ions
Bonding pairs and lone pairs as charge clouds that repel each other
Pairs arrange as far apart as possible to minimise repulsion
Repulsion order: lone pair–lone pair > lone pair–bond pair > bond pair–bond pair
Explain shapes and bond angles in molecules/ions with up to six electron pairs surrounding the central atom
3.1.3.6 Bond Polarity
Electronegativity: power of an atom to attract the pair of electrons in a covalent bond
Unsymmetrical electron distribution → polar covalent bond → possible permanent dipole
Use partial charges to show bond polarity
Explain why some molecules with polar bonds have no permanent dipole
3.1.3.7 Forces Between Molecules
Permanent dipole–dipole forces
Induced dipole–dipole (van der Waals / dispersion / London) forces
Hydrogen bonding
Influence on melting and boiling points
Importance of hydrogen bonding in low density of ice and anomalous boiling points
3.1.4 Energetics
3.1.4.1 Enthalpy Change
Reactions can be endothermic or exothermic
Enthalpy change (ΔH): heat energy change at constant pressure
Standard conditions: 100 kPa and stated temperature (e.g. ΔH₂₉₈°)
Define: standard enthalpy of combustion (ΔcH°) and standard enthalpy of formation (ΔfH°)
3.1.4.2 Calorimetry
q = mcΔT (m = mass, c = specific heat capacity, ΔT = temperature change)
Use to calculate molar enthalpy change for a reaction
Required Practical 2: Measurement of an enthalpy change.

3.1.4.3 Applications of Hess's Law
Hess's law
Use Hess's law to calculate enthalpy changes from enthalpies of combustion or formation
3.1.4.4 Bond Enthalpies
Mean bond enthalpy definition
Use mean bond enthalpies to calculate approximate ΔH for gaseous reactions
Explain why values differ from Hess's law calculations
3.1.5 Kinetics
3.1.5.1 Collision Theory
Reactions occur when collisions have sufficient energy
Activation energy definition
Explain why most collisions do not lead to a reaction
3.1.5.2 Maxwell–Boltzmann Distribution
Distribution of molecular energies in gases
Draw and interpret distribution curves for different temperatures
3.1.5.3 Effect of Temperature on Reaction Rate
Meaning of rate of reaction
Qualitative effect of temperature on rate
Use Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution to explain why small temperature increase → large rate increase
Required Practical 3: Investigation of how the rate of a reaction changes with temperature.

3.1.5.4 Effect of Concentration and Pressure
Qualitative effect of concentration on collision frequency
Qualitative effect of gas pressure on collision frequency
Explain how changes influence rate
3.1.5.5 Catalysts
A catalyst increases rate without being changed in composition or amount
Catalysts provide an alternative route of lower activation energy
Use Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution to explain catalytic effect
3.1.6 Chemical Equilibria, Le Chatelier's Principle and Kc
3.1.6.1 Chemical Equilibria and Le Chatelier's Principle
Many reactions are reversible
At equilibrium: forward and reverse rates equal; concentrations of reactants/products constant
Le Chatelier's principle: predict effects of changes in temperature, pressure, concentration on equilibrium position
A catalyst does not affect equilibrium position
Explain compromise temperature/pressure in industrial processes
3.1.6.2 Equilibrium Constant Kc for Homogeneous Systems
Kc deduced from reversible reaction equation
 represents concentration in mol dm⁻³
Kc not affected by concentration changes or catalyst addition
Construct Kc expressions; calculate Kc from equilibrium concentrations
Perform calculations involving Kc
Predict qualitative effects of temperature on Kc
3.1.7 Oxidation, Reduction and Redox Equations
Oxidation: electron loss; oxidising agents are electron acceptors
Reduction: electron gain; reducing agents are electron donors
Rules for assigning oxidation states
Work out oxidation state from formula
Write half-equations identifying oxidation and reduction
Combine half-equations to give overall redox equation
3.1.8 Thermodynamics (A-Level Only)
3.1.8.1 Born–Haber Cycles
Lattice enthalpy (lattice dissociation or lattice formation)
Born–Haber cycles use:
Enthalpy of formation
Ionisation energy
Enthalpy of atomisation
Bond enthalpy
Electron affinity
Construct Born–Haber cycles to calculate lattice enthalpies or other enthalpy changes
Compare lattice enthalpies from Born–Haber cycles with perfect ionic model → evidence for covalent character
Enthalpy of hydration definition
Cycles to calculate enthalpies of solution from lattice enthalpies and enthalpies of hydration
3.1.8.2 Gibbs Free-Energy Change (ΔG) and Entropy Change (ΔS)
ΔH alone is not sufficient to explain feasible change
Entropy change (ΔS): concept of increasing disorder
ΔG = ΔH – TΔS (derivation not required)
For a feasible reaction: ΔG ≤ 0
Calculate entropy changes from absolute entropy values
Determine how ΔG varies with temperature
Determine temperature at which a reaction becomes feasible
3.1.9 Rate Equations (A-Level Only)
3.1.9.1 Rate Equations
Rate = k[A]ᵐ[B]ⁿ
m, n = orders of reaction (restricted to 0, 1, 2)
k = rate constant
k = Ae⁻ᴱᵃ/ᴿᵀ (Arrhenius equation)
A = Arrhenius constant, Ea = activation energy, T = temperature in K
Define order of reaction and rate constant
Perform calculations using rate equation
Explain qualitative effect of temperature on k
Perform calculations using Arrhenius equation
Rearrange to ln k = –Ea/RT + ln A and use to plot straight line graph with slope –Ea/R
3.1.9.2 Determination of Rate Equation
Rate equation is experimentally determined
Orders provide information about reaction mechanism
Use concentration–time graphs to deduce rate
Use initial concentration–time data to deduce initial rate
Use rate–concentration data/graphs to deduce order (0, 1, 2)
Derive rate equation from orders
Use orders to identify rate determining/limiting step
Required Practical 7: Measuring the rate of reaction by an initial rate method and by a continuous monitoring method.

3.1.10 Equilibrium Constant Kp for Homogeneous Systems (A-Level Only)
Kp calculated from partial pressures at constant temperature
Derive partial pressure from mole fraction and total pressure
Construct Kp expressions; perform calculations
Predict qualitative effects of temperature and pressure on equilibrium position
Predict qualitative effects of temperature on Kp
Catalyst affects rate of attainment but not Kp value
3.1.11 Electrode Potentials and Electrochemical Cells (A-Level Only)
3.1.11.1 Electrode Potentials and Cells
IUPAC convention for half-equations
Conventional cell representation
Measuring electrode potentials using standard hydrogen electrode
Standard electrode potential (E°): 298 K, 100 kPa, 1.00 mol dm⁻³
Electrochemical series
Use E° values to predict direction of redox reactions
Calculate EMF of a cell
Write and apply conventional cell representation
Required Practical 8: Measuring the EMF of an electrochemical cell.

3.1.11.2 Commercial Applications of Electrochemical Cells
Electrochemical cells as commercial electrical energy source
Lithium cell simplified electrode reactions:
Positive electrode: Li⁺ + CoO₂ + e⁻ → Li⁺[CoO₂]⁻
Negative electrode: Li → Li⁺ + e⁻
Non-rechargeable (irreversible), rechargeable, and fuel cells
Alkaline hydrogen–oxygen fuel cell electrode reactions
Benefits and risks to society
Use given electrode data to deduce reactions, EMF, and current generation
3.1.12 Acids and Bases (A-Level Only)
3.1.12.1 Brønsted–Lowry Acid–Base Equilibria
Acid = proton donor; Base = proton acceptor
Acid–base equilibria involve proton transfer
3.1.12.2 Definition and Determination of pH
pH = –log₁₀[H⁺]
Convert [H⁺] to pH and vice versa
Calculate pH of a strong acid from its concentration
3.1.12.3 The Ionic Product of Water, Kw
Water is slightly dissociated
Kw = [H⁺][OH⁻]
Kw varies with temperature
Use Kw to calculate pH of a strong base from its concentration
3.1.12.4 Weak Acids and Bases, Ka
Weak acids/bases dissociate only slightly in aqueous solution
Ka = dissociation constant for a weak acid
pKa = –log₁₀Ka
Construct Ka expression; perform calculations relating pH, concentration and Ka
Convert between Ka and pKa
3.1.12.5 pH Curves, Titrations and Indicators
Perform calculations for titrations based on experimental results
Typical pH curves for all combinations of weak/strong monoprotic acids and bases
Sketch and explain shapes of pH curves
Use pH curves to select appropriate indicator
Required Practical 9: Investigate how pH changes when a weak acid reacts with a strong base and when a strong acid reacts with a weak base.

3.1.12.6 Buffer Action
Buffer solution maintains approximately constant pH despite dilution or small additions of acid/base
Acidic buffer: weak acid + salt of that weak acid
Basic buffer: weak base + salt of that weak base
Applications of buffer solutions
Explain qualitatively the action of acidic and basic buffers
Calculate pH of acidic buffer solutions
