CaO or CaCO₃ to remove SO₂ from flue gases
Relative solubilities of sulfates (Mg–Ba): MgSO₄ soluble → BaSO₄ insoluble
Test for sulfate ions: acidified BaCl₂ solution
Use of BaSO₄ in medicine
Required Practical 4: Carry out simple test-tube reactions to identify cations (Group 2, NH₄⁺) and anions (halide ions, OH⁻, CO₃²⁻, SO₄²⁻).

3.2.3 Group 7(17), the Halogens
3.2.3.1 Trends in Properties
Trends in electronegativity and boiling point
Trend in oxidising ability down the group (including displacement reactions of halide ions)
Trend in reducing ability of halide ions (including reactions of solid sodium halides with concentrated H₂SO₄)
Test for halide ions: acidified silver nitrate solution
Trend in solubility of silver halides in ammonia
Explain why silver nitrate is used, why it's acidified, and why ammonia is added
3.2.3.2 Uses of Chlorine and Chlorate(I)
Reaction of chlorine with water → Cl⁻ and ClO⁻ ions
Reaction of chlorine with water → Cl⁻ and O₂
Benefits vs risks of adding chemicals to water supplies
Use of chlorine in water treatment (benefits outweigh toxic effects)
Reaction of chlorine with cold, dilute NaOH; uses of the solution
3.2.4 Properties of Period 3 Elements and Their Oxides (A-Level Only)
Reactions of Na and Mg with water
Trends in reactions of Na, Mg, Al, Si, P, S with oxygen:
Na₂O, MgO, Al₂O₃, SiO₂, P₄O₁₀, SO₂, SO₃
Trend in melting point of highest oxides (Na–S)
Reactions of oxides (Na₂O, MgO, Al₂O₃, SiO₂, P₄O₁₀, SO₂, SO₃) with water and pH of solutions formed
Structures of acids and anions formed when P₄O₁₀, SO₂, SO₃ react with water
Explain melting point trend in terms of structure/bonding
Explain oxide–water reaction trends in terms of bonding type
Write equations for reactions of oxides with given acids and bases
3.2.5 Transition Metals (A-Level Only)
3.2.5.1 General Properties
Transition metal characteristics (Ti–Cu) arise from incomplete d sub-level in atoms or ions
Characteristic properties:
Complex formation
Formation of coloured ions
Variable oxidation state
Catalytic activity
Ligand: molecule/ion that donates electron pair to form co-ordinate bond with transition metal
Complex: central metal atom/ion surrounded by ligands
Co-ordination number: number of co-ordinate bonds to central metal
3.2.5.2 Substitution Reactions
Monodentate ligands: H₂O, NH₃, Cl⁻
NH₃ and H₂O similar in size, uncharged → exchange without change of co-ordination number (e.g. Co²⁺, Cu²⁺)
Substitution may be incomplete (e.g. [Cu(NH₃)₄(H₂O)₂]²⁺)
Cl⁻ larger than NH₃/H₂O → exchange of H₂O by Cl⁻ can change co-ordination number (e.g. Co²⁺, Cu²⁺, Fe³⁺)
Bidentate ligands: H₂NCH₂CH₂NH₂ (en), C₂O₄²⁻
Multidentate ligands: EDTA⁴⁻
Haem: iron(II) complex with multidentate ligand; O₂ forms co-ordinate bond to Fe(II) in haemoglobin
CO toxicity: replaces O₂ co-ordinately bonded to Fe(II)
Chelate effect: bidentate/multidentate ligands replace monodentate ligands
Explained by entropy/enthalpy balance
3.2.5.3 Shapes of Complex Ions
Octahedral complexes: small ligands (H₂O, NH₃)
Cis–trans isomerism with monodentate ligands
Optical isomerism with bidentate ligands
Tetrahedral complexes: larger ligands (Cl⁻)
Square planar complexes: can display cis–trans isomerism
Cisplatin is the cis isomer
Linear complex: Ag⁺ forms [Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺ (Tollens' reagent)
3.2.5.4 Formation of Coloured Ions
Colour arises when some wavelengths of visible light are absorbed
d electrons move from ground state to excited state
ΔE = hν = hc/λ
Changes in oxidation state, co-ordination number and ligand alter ΔE → colour change
Colorimetry to determine concentration of coloured ions
3.2.5.5 Variable Oxidation States
Vanadium species in oxidation states V, IV, III, II (reduction of vanadate(V) by zinc in acid)
Redox potential influenced by pH and ligand
Tollens' reagent [Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺ reduced to metallic silver: distinguishes aldehydes from ketones
Redox titrations: Fe²⁺ and C₂O₄²⁻ with MnO₄⁻
Perform calculations for these and similar redox reactions
3.2.5.6 Catalysts
Transition metals/compounds act as heterogeneous and homogeneous catalysts
Heterogeneous catalyst: different phase; reaction at active sites on surface
Support medium maximises surface area, minimises cost
V₂O₅ in the Contact process
Fe in the Haber process
Can be poisoned by impurities blocking active sites
Homogeneous catalyst: same phase; reaction via intermediate species
Fe²⁺ catalyses I⁻ + S₂O₈²⁻ reaction
Mn²⁺ autocatalyses C₂O₄²⁻ + MnO₄⁻ reaction
Explain importance of variable oxidation states in catalysis
3.2.6 Reactions of Ions in Aqueous Solution (A-Level Only)
Metal-aqua ions formed:
[M(H₂O)₆]²⁺ (M = Fe, Cu)
[M(H₂O)₆]³⁺ (M = Al, Fe)
Acidity of [M(H₂O)₆]³⁺ > [M(H₂O)₆]²⁺ (explained by charge/size ratio)
Some metal hydroxides are amphoteric (e.g. Al³⁺ hydroxide dissolves in acids and bases)
Test-tube reactions of M²⁺ (Fe, Cu) and M³⁺ (Al, Fe) with OH⁻, NH₃, CO₃²⁻
Required Practical 11: Carry out simple test-tube reactions to identify transition metal ions in aqueous solution.

3.3 Organic Chemistry
3.3.1 Introduction to Organic Chemistry
3.3.1.1 Nomenclature
Organic compounds represented by:

Empirical, molecular, general, structural, displayed and skeletal formulas
Homologous series: same functional group
IUPAC nomenclature rules (chains and rings up to six carbon atoms each)
3.3.1.2 Reaction Mechanisms
Free-radical mechanisms:

Unpaired electron represented by a dot
Curly arrows not required
Write balanced equations for steps
Other mechanisms:

Curly arrow from lone pair or bond → formation of covalent bond
Curly arrow from bond → breaking of covalent bond
3.3.1.3 Isomerism
Structural isomerism: chain, position and functional group isomers
Stereoisomerism:
E–Z isomerism: restricted rotation about C=C double bond
Cahn–Ingold–Prelog (CIP) priority rules
3.3.2 Alkanes
3.3.2.1 Fractional Distillation of Crude Oil
Alkanes are saturated hydrocarbons
Petroleum separated by fractional distillation
3.3.2.2 Modification of Alkanes by Cracking
Thermal cracking: high pressure, high temperature → high % alkenes
Catalytic cracking: slight pressure, high temperature, zeolite catalyst → motor fuels, aromatic hydrocarbons
Economic reasons for cracking
3.3.2.3 Combustion of Alkanes
Used as fuels; complete or incomplete combustion
Internal combustion engine pollutants: NOₓ, CO, carbon, unburned hydrocarbons
Catalytic converters remove gaseous pollutants
Combustion of sulfur-containing hydrocarbons → SO₂ → air pollution
SO₂ removal from flue gases using CaO or CaCO₃
3.3.2.4 Chlorination of Alkanes
Reaction of methane with chlorine
Free-radical substitution mechanism: initiation, propagation, termination steps
3.3.3 Halogenoalkanes
3.3.3.1 Nucleophilic Substitution
