Carbon–halogen bond enthalpy influences rate of reaction
3.3.3.2 Elimination
Concurrent substitution and elimination (e.g. 2-bromopropane with KOH)
Explain role of reagent as both nucleophile and base
Outline mechanisms
3.3.3.3 Ozone Depletion
Ozone in upper atmosphere absorbs UV radiation
UV breaks C–Cl bonds in CFCs → Cl atoms
Cl atoms catalyse ozone decomposition:
Cl• + O₃ → ClO• + O₂
ClO• + O₃ → 2O₂ + Cl•
Evidence led to legislation banning CFCs
Development of chlorine-free alternatives
3.3.4 Alkenes
3.3.4.1 Structure, Bonding and Reactivity
Alkenes are unsaturated hydrocarbons
Double bond = centre of high electron density
3.3.4.2 Addition Reactions of Alkenes
Electrophilic addition with HBr, H₂SO₄, Br₂
Bromine test for unsaturation
Major and minor products in unsymmetrical alkene additions
Outline mechanisms; explain by relative stabilities of primary, secondary, tertiary carbocation intermediates
3.3.4.3 Addition Polymers
Formed from alkenes and substituted alkenes
Repeating units; IUPAC naming rules
Addition polymers are unreactive
Typical uses of PVC; properties modified using plasticiser
Draw repeating units/monomers; explain unreactivity; explain intermolecular forces in polyalkenes
3.3.5 Alcohols
3.3.5.1 Alcohol Production
Industrial production by hydration of alkenes (acid catalyst)
Fermentation of glucose → ethanol; conditions
Ethanol as a biofuel (fractional distillation to separate)
Carbon neutrality arguments and limitations
Environmental/ethical issues of biofuel use
